Brazil is one of the countries most affected by the COVID-19 pandemic, with more than 16 million confirmed cases and 454 429 confirmed deaths by May 26, 2021 (according to the Johns Hopkins Coronavirus Resource Center).

Brazil was and still is one of the countries most impacted by the first wave of Covid-19 which first recorded case on 26th February 2020 and reached community transmission from 20th March 2019 onwards to dates, that caught Brazil unprepared and unable to response due to the strain on hospital capacity such as the intense and lengthy request for ICU (incentive care unit) beds, professionals, personal protection equipment and healthcare resources.

I will perform an Exploratory Data Analysis on Covid-19 data found from this dataset.

Exploratory Data Analysis is a technique used by data scientists to analyse the data prior to utilizing machine learning models. It allows for a more informed preparation of the data, and therefore more accurate machine learning models down the line.

We will need to predict whether or not the patient will need to be admitted to the ICU based on their characteristics provided in this data.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Let's have a look at the data description for the competition and see what valuable information we can extract:¶
  1. The dataset consists of the following information:
    • Patient demographic information
    • Patient previous grouped diseases
    • Blood results
    • Vital signs
  2. In total there are 54 features, and more if we include the variations, such as mean, median, max, min, diff and relative diff. Diff is calculated by (max - min) whilst relative diff by (diff/median)
  3. Data has been cleaned and scaled by column according to Min Max Scaler to fit between -1 and 1. Thus, removing -1's is not a right thing to do here
  4. ICU admissions should be considered as the target variable
  5. The data for each patient is split into 5 rows rather than 1, as indicated by the image below. Each row represents the time it took to get the person into the ICU. We will confirm that with head and tail commands.

Adding ICU_ADMISSIONS¶

Our investigation earlier did in fact confirm that there are 5 rows for each patient, in Patient Visit Identifier.¶

The initial investigation directs my next steps into following actions:

  1. Merge the 5 rows into 1, which will be accomplised by
    • Adding a new column ICU_ADMISSIONS, which will tell us whether or not the patient was admitted at all
    • Dropping the window columns and values in 0-2 window, as both will not be useful to us in the later stages.
In [9]:
data = data.loc[~((data['WINDOW'] == '0-2') & (data['ICU'] == 1))]

icu_admission = data.groupby('PATIENT_VISIT_IDENTIFIER').agg({'ICU': max}).reset_index().rename(columns={'ICU': 'ICU_ADMISSIONS'})
    
data = data.merge(icu_admission, on=['PATIENT_VISIT_IDENTIFIER'], how='left')

data.drop(['WINDOW','ICU'],axis = 1,inplace=True)

print('NaN values =', data.isnull().sum().sum())
print("""""")

vars_with_missing = []

for feature in data.columns:
    missings = data[feature].isna().sum()
    
    if missings > 0 :
        vars_with_missing.append(feature)
        missings_perc = missings / data.shape[0]
        
        print('Variable {} has {} records ({:.2%}) with missing values.'.format(feature, missings, missings_perc))
print('In total, there are {} variables with missing values'.format(len(vars_with_missing)))

As we can see, there is a lot of missing values in many different columns. I believe the only sensible approach to dealing with this issue would be to merge the rows, as discussed earlier.¶
There is, however, one patient (1 patient = 5 records) who misses his initial records. I'd like to remove him manually in order to prevent this issue skewing the data during the merge for these columns. This is due to the fact that the fields that I mention (Disease Grouping through Other) are either 1's or 0's. The nans would create values such as 0.2 or 0.25.¶
In the next step, we need to take care of the data types to allow for the means to be extracted. Afterwards, we will drop the empty patient¶

vars_with_missing = []

for feature in data.columns:
    missings = data[feature].isna().sum()
    
    if missings > 0 :
        vars_with_missing.append(feature)
        missings_perc = missings / data.shape[0]
        
        print('Variable {} has {} records ({:.2%}) with missing values.'.format(feature, missings, missings_perc))
print('In total, there are {} variables with missing values'.format(len(vars_with_missing)))

First feature checks¶

Since we now have no missing values in some columns, we can check them now and decide whether or not we want to carry them over through the merge. I want to, however, carry over all of the vital signs, as to be able to compare them with other vital signs. That leaves us with the patient characteristics, such as age or gender.¶

col = 0

for i in range(len(disease_grp)):
    sns.countplot(x=disease_grp[i], hue="ICU_ADMISSIONS", data=data, ax = axes[int((i)/2)][col])
    col = (col+1) % 2
Just by looking at those bars, we can conclude the following:¶
  1. Most of these features are highly imbalanced, speaking about:
    • HTN
    • IMMUNOCOMPROMISED
    • OTHER
    • DISEASE GROUPINGS 1-6 These nine features are highly imbalanced, and their ICU Admissions are very similar on both sides. The best course of action will be to drop them.
  2. Gender is quite imbalanced, but not as much as the other two. Further investigation required to confirm whether or not it should be removed.
  3. There seems to be a relation between being older and more ICU admissions. It should be retained for the merge, and we will check the correlations just to confirm this.
In [30]:
data_test = data[['AGE_ABOVE65','AGE_PERCENTIL','GENDER','ICU_ADMISSIONS']].copy()
heatmap = sb.heatmap(data_test.corr(), annot = True)
plt.show()
There seems to be no correlation between GENDER and ICU_ADMISSIONS, so we should drop it. There is, however, some correlation between AGE and ICU_ADMISSIONS, we will thus retain these values.¶

Feature Engineering¶

After the merge, there was still one patient that had some null values attached. I've dealt with it swiftly and mercilessly, and now, as indicated per the last command, there are no more null values in the dataset.¶
We should now start looking into this data, and find the ones that correlate the most with the target value. I will write a function that will print the correlations between ICU_ADMISSIONS and each other column, except for PATIENT_VISIT_IDENTIFIER and itself.¶

function_data = merged_data.drop(['PATIENT_VISIT_IDENTIFIER','ICU_ADMISSIONS'], axis=1)
# Function will check the correlation between two columns. It will round the correlation, as well as
#skip any nan values, which cannot be rounded. All of these values will go into a dictionary, and
#are also being printed
def correlation():
    dictionary = {}
    for column in function_data.columns:
        correl = round(merged_data['ICU_ADMISSIONS'].corr(function_data[column]),3)
        if pd.isna(correl) == True:
            pass
        print(f"Correlation between ICU_ADMISSIONS and {column} is equal to {correl}")
        dictionary[column] = correl
    return dictionary

dictionary = correlation()

There are three observations that we can take from these correlations:¶
  1. Many features have the same correlation percentage
    • Features such as Calcium, and their variances (such as Median, Mean etc.) have the same value of correlation, being -0.178.
  2. Diffs are presented as nans
    • Most of the diffs have a correlation of nan. I believe I should drop all columns that have this type of relationship, as it may introduce problems for my model later on
  3. Many values are negative
    • For instance, aforementioned calcium has a negative correlation with the ICU_Admissions. According to this: https://datascience.stackexchange.com/questions/78166/can-features-negatively-correlated-with-the-target-be-used, I should retain them, as the negative correlations are just as important as positive values. The only ones that should be removed are the ones with almost no correlation

We have a dictionary with each correlation, so we now should remove all of the dictionary entries that contain the nan. Afterwards, we should remove the repeating features with same correlation.

#Here, we create a list of null correlated features which should be removed
deletion_list = []
for key, value in dictionary.items():
    if pd.isna(value) == True:
        deletion_list.append(key)

print(deletion_list)

Feature Selection¶

Now that we have a dataset which is much less cluttered, we can begin to select the most appropriate features for our model.¶
I would like to train the model on four different datasets:¶
  1. The one with the most features, so the final_data from before
  2. One that had only the least correlated features removed, but still contains a lot of them
  3. One that contains only the most correlated features
  4. One that contains only the most positive correlated features

For these to be created, i need to find out:

  1. What the maximum and minimum correlations were
  2. What is the minimum correlation that I should use for the dataset # 2
  3. How many features should I consider for the dataset # 3, and # 4, to only include the most correlated ones.

First of all, let us rerun the correlation function to create a dictionary with the new correlation values:

In [60]:
def correlation():
    dictionary = {}
    for column in final_data.columns:
        correl = round(final_data['ICU_ADMISSIONS'].corr(final_data[column]),3)
        print(f"Correlation between ICU_ADMISSIONS and {column} is equal to {correl}")
        dictionary[column] = correl
    return dictionary

dictionary = correlation()

Data Training¶

With data preprocessing and splitting done, we should now train those datasets and see how well each of them performs. The task requires us to pick three algorithms, therefore I will pick the following:¶
  1. Decision Tree, as it is one of the more basic algorithms, and it can serve as a baseline for our calculations
  2. Random Forest, as it is an improved version of a decision tree, and a good algorithm for linearly separable data
  3. XGBOOST, as it is a tree-based ensemble learning algorithm, meaning it is different from the other two algorithms. By using different algorithms we will have a clearer understanding of which method works the best in regards to this dataset.
In [78]:
clfs = {"Decision Tree": DecisionTreeClassifier(),
          "Random Forest":RandomForestClassifier(),
          "XGBOOST":XGBClassifier(verbosity=0)}
In [79]:
def model_fit(clfs,x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test):
    fitted_model={}
    model_result = pd.DataFrame()
    for model_name, model in clfs.items():
        model.fit(x_train,y_train)
        fitted_model.update({model_name:model})
        y_pred = model.predict(x_test)
        model_dict = {}
        model_dict['1.Algorithm'] = model_name
        model_dict['2. Accuracy'] = round(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred),3)
        model_dict['3. Precision']= round(precision_score(y_test, y_pred),3)
        model_dict['4. Recall'] = round(recall_score(y_test,y_pred),3)
        model_result = model_result.append(model_dict,ignore_index=True)
    return fitted_model, model_result

The results are as follows:¶

  1. In Dataset 1:
    • The most commonly used algorithm is random forest, which also gives the highest accuracy of 0.935. It was, on average, the least accurate dataset.
  2. In Dataset 2:
    • The most commonly used algorithm is random forest, which also gives the highest accuracy of 0.922. XGBOOST, when it was proved the most accurate, also provided us with the same score. In terms of average accuracy, it is on the second place, however the results are more consistently high, so it would most likely be on the first place if more samples were taken.
  3. In Dataset 3:
    • The most commonly used algorithm is random forest, however the most accurate accuracy came from XGBOOST, which gave us an astounding 0.974. In terms of accuracy, it is on the first place. I believe, however, that if more samples were taken, then it would lose that spot as the 0.974 is boosting the rest, less accurate results up.
  4. In Dataset 4:
    • Both algorithms were used equally, however the highest accuracy was provided with XGBOOST, which gave us 0.948. In terms of average accuracy, it is on the third place.
As we can see, whilst random forest was used the most amount of times, it was XGBOOST that usually gave us the highest accuracy.¶
When it comes to the average prediction accuracy, it seems that the approach of dataset 3, which had the 10 max and 10 min values, seemed to work the best on average. I do believe however that dataset 2 approach with 50 features gives more consistent high scores, and it should be the preferred approach.¶
Since dataset 2 is the one that I believe is the best approach, it means that random forest is also the best algorithm for this dataset¶
